   "source": [
    "The target variable **jobs** (retail job openings, in thousands) shows a clear upward trend from roughly 2,800 in early 2016 to over 7,600 by the end of 2024. There is a pronounced seasonal pattern with recurring peaks around April, July, and October, and consistent dips in February and December.\n",
    "\n",
    "The correlation structure is heavily influenced by shared trends. **Wages** (0.95) and **quits** (0.83) both trend upward alongside jobs, so their high correlations are largely spurious (trend driven). **Sales** shows a moderate positive relationship (0.37), while **layoffs** are essentially uncorrelated with jobs (-0.05) and remain relatively flat over the entire sample.\n",
    "\n",
    "One notable feature is that COVID-19 did not produce a visible dip in retail job openings. Unlike most industries, retail experienced an acceleration in hiring demand beginning around late 2019 and early 2020. This represents a meaningful structural shift in the data that will be relevant later when choosing training windows."
