   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Structural Break Analysis & Training Window Selection\n",
    "\n",
    "All the models fitted above train on data going back to January 2016 and extrapolate the growth trend they learn from that period. But looking at the series more carefully, there appears to be a structural shift in the US retail labor market around late 2019 and early 2020.\n",
    "\n",
    "The COVID-19 pandemic did not reduce retail job openings the way it did in other sectors. Instead, the retail industry saw an unprecedented acceleration in labor demand beginning around this time, driven by the surge in e-commerce, supply chain disruptions requiring more warehouse and logistics workers, and shifting consumer spending patterns. The series effectively jumped to a new, higher level and began fluctuating around that level rather than continuing to grow at the pre-COVID rate.\n",
    "\n",
    "If this structural shift is real, then training on the full 2016 to 2023 period forces models to fit a growth trajectory that spans two fundamentally different regimes. The pre-COVID regime (2016 to 2019) was characterized by steady, moderate growth in retail job openings. The post-COVID regime (2020 onward) operates at a higher level with a much flatter or even plateauing trend. A model that blends both regimes will overestimate the growth rate going forward.\n",
    "\n",
    "To test this hypothesis, we examine how forecast accuracy changes when we restrict the training window to more recent data."
   ]
