   "source": [
    "**Domain Context: Post-Pandemic Labor Market Normalization**\n",
    "\n",
    "The structural break identified in our data is consistent with broader labor market research. According to the BLS Monthly Labor Review, annual job openings declined for the first time since the pandemic recession in 2023, dropping from 11.2 million to 9.4 million, with continued declines through 2024 (BLS, 2024). The Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis finds that adjusted vacancy rates have now fallen \"well below pre-pandemic levels,\" suggesting the post-COVID surge in labor demand has not just moderated but reversed (Engbom & Karahan, 2024). The Cleveland Fed documents that the vacancy-to-unemployment ratio approximately doubled by mid-2022 then normalized rapidly, and notes that \"linear models\" estimated on historical data struggled to capture these post-pandemic dynamics (Verbrugge & Zaman, 2024). Research from the Federal Reserve Board confirms that standard time-series models trained on pre-pandemic data persistently misforecast during structural breaks because they default to historical persistence patterns (Bodenstein et al., 2021).\n",
    "\n",
    "For the retail sector specifically, the BLS projects retail trade as the only major sector expected to lose jobs over the projection period, driven by continued e-commerce growth and structural transformation (BLS, 2024). This reinforces the case that extrapolating pre-2020 retail job openings growth into 2025 would be inappropriate.\n",
    "\n",
    "**References:**\n",
    "- BLS (2024). \"Job openings and hires decline in 2023 as the labor market cools.\" *Monthly Labor Review*. https://www.bls.gov/opub/mlr/2024/article/job-openings-and-hires-decline-in-2023.htm\n",
    "- Engbom, N. & Karahan, F. (2024). \"Fewer openings, harder to get hired.\" *Federal Reserve Bank of Minneapolis*. https://www.minneapolisfed.org/article/2024/fewer-openings-harder-to-get-hired-us-labor-market-likely-softer-than-it-appears\n",
    "- Verbrugge, R. & Zaman, S. (2024). \"Understanding Post-Pandemic Surprises in Inflation and the Labor Market.\" *Federal Reserve Bank of Cleveland, Economic Commentary*. https://www.clevelandfed.org/publications/economic-commentary/2024/ec-202411-understanding-postpandemic-surprises\n",
    "- Bodenstein, M. et al. (2021). \"Forecasting During the COVID-19 Pandemic.\" *FEDS Notes, Federal Reserve Board*. https://www.federalreserve.gov/econres/notes/feds-notes/forecasting-during-the-covid-19-pandemic-a-structural-analysis-of-downside-risk-20210201.html"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The year-over-year growth rate tells a nuanced story. Pre-COVID, growth was steady but decelerating (from ~15% in 2017 down to ~6% in 2019). The pandemic triggered a massive spike in growth (17% in 2020 and 2021) as retail labor demand surged. After the peak, growth appeared to moderate sharply in 2022 and 2023 (5% and 4.5%), but then 2024 rebounded to 16%.\n",
    "\n",
    "The key observation is not a clean deceleration but rather high volatility in growth rates. The series alternates between years of rapid expansion and years of near-stagnation. This volatility is precisely what makes trend extrapolation risky: a differenced model (d=1) estimates a single average growth rate from the training period and applies it going forward. If the true growth rate fluctuates between 5% and 17% year to year, the \"average\" growth rate will overshoot in flat years and undershoot in expansion years.\n",
    "\n",
    "A level-stationary model sidesteps this problem. Rather than committing to a fixed growth trajectory, it forecasts the current regime's mean level with seasonal adjustments and lets the AR dynamics adapt. This is the more conservative and robust choice when the growth rate is this volatile.\n",
    "\n",
    "The choice of October 2019 as the window start captures the full post-COVID regime (including the rapid growth and the subsequent moderation) while providing 63 observations for reliable seasonal estimation across more than 5 complete annual cycles.\n",
    "\n",
    "The formal structural break tests above confirm this regime change is statistically significant. The Chow test's identification of April 2020 as the break point, combined with the volatile and non-monotonic growth rates, makes trend extrapolation particularly risky for the 2025 forecast horizon."
