   "source": [
    "The top panel shows the 2024 internal test. The full-data trended models (SARIMA with d=1,D=1 and ETS with additive trend) are actually closer to the 2024 observed values than our short-window model. This makes sense: 2024 was still a year of growth in retail job openings, so models that extrapolate the historical trend happen to land in the right neighborhood. The short-window model, with no trend component, forecasts closer to the 2020 through 2023 average level and undershoots.\n",
    "\n",
    "However, the bottom panel reveals why trend extrapolation is dangerous. When we extend the forecast horizon to 24 months, the trended models continue climbing well beyond any level observed in the historical data. The SARIMA with differencing and ETS with additive trend both project an increasingly steep upward path, pushing forecasts into unrealistic territory by the second year. Our level-stationary model, by contrast, settles into a stable seasonal cycle around the current regime's mean.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the core tradeoff. The trended models look better on 2024 because they benefit from the tail end of the growth period. But using them to forecast 2025 means betting that the growth will continue at the same rate. The evidence from the last few years suggests otherwise: the rate of increase in retail job openings has clearly decelerated compared to 2020 through 2022. Our model makes the more conservative assumption that the series has entered a plateau, forecasting the level and seasonal pattern without projecting additional growth. This is a deliberate, domain-informed choice that prioritizes robustness over the apparent short-term accuracy of trend-following models.\n",
    "\n",
    "This divergence aligns with what the Cleveland Fed describes as the failure of \"linear models\" to capture post-pandemic dynamics. The trended specifications extrapolate the 2016 to 2024 growth rate indefinitely. In a labor market that the BLS and Federal Reserve consistently describe as normalizing and cooling, such extrapolation is economically implausible. The no-trend model's forecast of stabilization around 7,200 is more consistent with the direction indicated by recent data and institutional research."
