   "source": [
    "On the short-window internal test (51 training observations, 12 test), ETS models outperform SARIMA. The best ETS variant (with additive trend) achieves substantially lower RMSE than the no-trend SARIMA. Even ETS models without trend produce lower test RMSE.\n",
    "\n",
    "This result is expected: the 51-observation training window is dominated by the post-COVID surge (2020 through 2022), which pushes the SARIMA's unconditional mean estimate well above the 2024 test values. The AR(1) forecast reverts toward this inflated mean, overshooting 2024. ETS, with its exponential smoothing of the level component, adapts more quickly to the recent decline.\n",
    "\n",
    "However, for the final 2025 forecast, we retrain on all 63 observations including 2024 data, which corrects the mean estimate. Our choice of SARIMA over ETS is driven by two considerations. First, the trended ETS variants that win the internal test would extrapolate growth into 2025, reintroducing the same problem we diagnosed with full-data models. Second, the SARIMA's explicit autoregressive structure with AR(1) near 0.95 provides a transparent, interpretable mechanism for level adaptation: the forecast anchors to the last observed value and decays toward the series mean with a known half-life.\n",
    "\n",
    "We accept worse internal test RMSE in exchange for a model whose forecast behavior is more consistent with the structural break evidence and domain knowledge. In applied forecasting, model selection is not purely a statistical exercise. When formal break tests, domain research from the BLS and Federal Reserve, and forecast trajectory analysis all point toward a normalizing labor market, we weight that convergent evidence alongside (and in this case above) a single internal test comparison conducted on a short, turbulent window. The SARIMA(1,0,0)(1,0,1,12) captures the essential dynamics: seasonal patterns, mean-reverting level, and no trend extrapolation."
