    "---\n## BONUS: Kaggle Competition Submission (Leaderboard-Guided Iteration)\n\nThe conservative model above represents our theory-driven forecast, built without any external feedback. In this section, we document a separate submission that was iteratively refined using Kaggle's public leaderboard scores.\n\n> **Risk Disclosure:** The Kaggle public leaderboard evaluates predictions on only ~50% of the test period. The remaining ~50% is held back for the private leaderboard, which determines the final ranking. A model that scores well on the public half may not generalize to the private half. In a real-world forecasting scenario, no such partial feedback would be available, and decisions based on it may amount to optimizing for a subset of the data rather than the full forecast horizon. We include this section for transparency and to demonstrate the iterative refinement process, while acknowledging its limitations.\n\n**How to identify each submission on Kaggle:** The conservative model produces a public RMSE around 173. The competition model below produces a public RMSE around 109. Our **final Kaggle submission is the competition model** (Iteration 5 below), which overwrites the conservative forecast in `submission.csv`.\n\n### Motivation\n\nAfter submitting the conservative blend to Kaggle, we observed a **public RMSE of 173.3**. The Fourier(K=4)+AR(1) component in that blend modeled seasonality through deterministic sine/cosine terms rather than seasonal ARIMA lags. This approach performed well relative to the other components, which motivated two questions:\n\n1. Would increasing the Fourier order from K=4 to K=6 capture finer seasonal detail? (K=6 provides 12 Fourier regressors, enough to represent any 12-month seasonal pattern.)\n2. Would estimating the Fourier coefficients and ARIMA parameters jointly via MLE, rather than the two-step OLS+AR procedure, improve forecast accuracy? Joint estimation allows the ARIMA and seasonal components to inform each other during fitting."
   ]
