  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Iteration 1: ARIMA(1,0,0) + Fourier(K=6), MLE on the Post-Break Window\n\nWe started by fitting a single ARIMA(1,0,0) model with K=6 Fourier exogenous regressors on the same post-break window used in the conservative model (November 2019 onward, 62 observations). Unlike the OLS+AR approach in the conservative Fourier(K=4), here `statsmodels.ARIMA` estimates all parameters jointly via maximum likelihood. This means the AR(1) coefficient and the 12 Fourier coefficients are estimated simultaneously, which provides regularization: the AR component absorbs serial correlation that the Fourier terms alone cannot capture, and the Fourier terms are estimated conditional on that correlation structure.\n\n**Kaggle result: public RMSE = 154.2** (down from 173.3 for the conservative blend). The improvement confirmed that the Fourier(K=6) + MLE approach captures seasonal dynamics more effectively than the conservative specification.\n\n### Iteration 2: ARIMA(3,0,1) + Fourier(K=6), MLE on a Longer Window\n\nIteration 1 used only 62 post-break observations. A natural question is whether including pre-COVID data would add useful seasonal information. We fitted the same Fourier(K=6) + ARIMA framework on a longer window starting June 2017 (91 observations).\n\nThe longer window spans the pre-COVID period of stable seasonal patterns (2017-2019) plus the COVID disruption and recovery (2020-2022) and the post-recovery normalization (2023-2024). To accommodate the additional complexity from including these different regimes, we used a higher-order ARIMA(3,0,1) specification. The additional AR and MA terms give the model flexibility to absorb the structural break dynamics that the short window avoids entirely. We selected (3,0,1) because it achieved the lowest AIC among the orders we tested on this window (shown in the code cell below).\n\n**Kaggle result: public RMSE = 202.7.** Individually, this model performed worse than Iteration 1. However, inspecting the month-by-month forecasts revealed a notably different error pattern. The short-window model (Iteration 1) and the long-window model (Iteration 2) tended to err in opposite directions for certain months, suggesting they capture complementary seasonal dynamics.\n\n### Iteration 3: Equal-Weight Blend of Short and Long Windows\n\nSince neither model dominated and their errors appeared complementary, we combined them with equal (50/50) weights following the forecast combination principles from the Day 9 lecture: when no single model is clearly superior, simple equal-weight averages reduce forecast variance and hedge against model misspecification.\n\n**Kaggle result: public RMSE = 127.8.** This is a substantial improvement over both individual models (154.2 and 202.7) and the conservative blend (173.3). The improvement illustrates the power of diversification: two models that individually score 154 and 203 can produce a blend that scores 128, because their errors partially cancel.\n\n### Iteration 4: AIC-Guided ARIMA Order Refinement\n\nAfter the success of the blend, we revisited the ARIMA order of the short-window model. Comparing AIC values for the Iteration 1 model:\n\n- ARIMA(1,0,0) + Fourier(K=6): AIC = 895.7\n- ARIMA(2,0,0) + Fourier(K=6): AIC = 878.5\n\nAIC favors AR(2) by 17 points, a substantial margin. The second autoregressive lag captures persistence at the two-month horizon that AR(1) does not model.\n\nAdditionally, with one more ARIMA parameter to estimate, sample size matters. Extending the short window from November 2019 (62 observations) to June 2019 (67 observations) provides 5 additional pre-COVID months while remaining well before the April 2020 structural break. On this extended window, the AIC preference for AR(2) is even stronger (delta AIC = -22), consistent with the longer sample providing more statistical power to identify the second lag.\n\nWe updated the short-window component to ARIMA(2,0,0) + Fourier(K=6) on the June 2019 window and blended it 50/50 with the original Iteration 2 long-window model.\n\n**Kaggle result: public RMSE = 118.0** (down from 127.8).\n\n### Iteration 5: Simplify the Long-Window Model\n\nThe blend now pairs ARIMA(2,0,0) on the short window with ARIMA(3,0,1) on the long window. We checked whether the long-window model also benefits from simplification:\n\n- ARIMA(3,0,1) + Fourier(K=6) on Jun 2017: AIC = 1301.3\n- ARIMA(2,0,0) + Fourier(K=6) on Jun 2017: AIC = 1301.3\n\nThe AICs are identical, but ARIMA(2,0,0) uses 2 parameters instead of 4. The principle of parsimony favors the simpler specification when fit is equivalent. Standardizing both components on ARIMA(2,0,0) + Fourier(K=6) also makes the blend conceptually cleaner: the same model structure applied to two different training windows, with the blend capturing the information from both time periods.\n\n**Kaggle result: public RMSE = 109.4.** This is our best score, representing a 37% improvement over the conservative blend (173.3 to 109.4)."
